  "prompt": "Do Go-Back-N ARQ and Selective Repeat ARQ use cumulative acknowledgements or an acknowledgement for every individual packet?",
  "response": "Go-Back-N ARQ and Selective Repeat ARQ handle acknowledgements differently:\n\n1. **Go-Back-N ARQ**: This protocol makes use of cumulative acknowledgements. In Go-Back-N, the receiver sends an acknowledgement for the highest sequence number of the data packets received in order without any gaps. If any packet is not received correctly, all subsequent packets are considered lost or out of order and must be retransmitted.\n\n2. **Selective Repeat ARQ**: Unlike Go-Back-N, Selective Repeat sends an acknowledgement for each individual packet. This allows the receiver to acknowledge packets individually, enabling the sender to retransmit only those specific packets that were not received correctly (i.e., those packets for which no acknowledgement was received). This can lead to more efficient use of the network as only the missing packets are retransmitted rather than needing to resend a larger block of packets as in Go-Back-N.\n\nIn summary, Go-Back-N uses cumulative acknowledgements while Selective Repeat ARQ uses an individual acknowledgement for each packet.",
